using `usedExports: "global"` "fixes" this issue.

no luck in making small reproduction...

Could you try some other flags too?

* `optimization.innerGraph: false`
* `optimization.concatenateModules: false`
* `optimization.sideEffects: false`
Maybe you can share your repo privately with me? Seems like a good repo to find more issue related to this...
I am asking my management about it. I hope it will be possible under NDA.
@Knagis Maybe you can found part of code what is broken?

@evilebottnawi unfortunately, not yet. I am finally releasing 5.3.1 with `usedExports: "global"` to my org, fingers crossed everything will work and I will get time to research this issue in more detail. Last night I could not get the module concatenation to concat a class together with something else at all (in a separate repro repo) - which seems to be the key since otherwise tslib will never be made conditional require.

@sokra I got approval, should I contact you using the e-mail on your git commits?

> @sokra I got approval, should I contact you using the e-mail on your git commits?

yep

I think I found the problem. At least I found one that is very similar.

It happens when the execution order in a concatenated module is different between runtimes

issue.title: handle the case when execution order in a concatenated module is runtime-dependent

repository.name: webpack
repository.description: A bundler for javascript and friends. Packs many modules into a few bundled assets. Code Splitting allows for loading parts of the application on demand. Through "loaders", modules can be CommonJs, AMD, ES6 modules, CSS, Images, JSON, Coffeescript, LESS, ... and your custom stuff.
